  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a uniformly charged sphere can be determined based on the distribution of charge and the principle of superposition. \n\n1. **Uniformly Charged Sphere (Solid)**: If the sphere is solid and uniformly charged with total charge \\( Q \\) and radius \\( R \\), the potential \\( V \\) at the center (and throughout the interior) of the sphere is given by:\n\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n   \\]\n\n   Here, \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) is the vacuum permittivity.\n\n2. **Uniformly Charged Thin Spherical Shell**: If the sphere is a thin spherical shell with total charge \\( Q \\) and radius \\( R \\), the potential at any point inside the shell, including the center, is the same as at the surface:\n\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{1}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n   \\]\n\nIn both cases, the electric potential at the center of the sphere depends only on the total charge \\( Q \\) and the radius \\( R \\) of the sphere. \n\nIn summary, whether the sphere is solid or a thin shell, the electric potential at the center can be expressed as:\n\n\\[\nV = \\frac{1}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0} \\cdot \\frac{Q}{R}\n\\] where \\( Q \\) is the total charge and \\( R \\) is the radius.",
